The Battle of the Dry Basin ended the Great Oasis's period of unified governance under the High Water Court.
The High Water Court had fractured into three factions: Pragmatists, Legalists, and Ritualists (proto-Jackal Synod).
The battle destroyed the Toll Pavilion and collapsed two of the four Cistern Ring chambers.
The last High Water Judge died in the engagement, leaving no legitimate successor under the existing charter framework.
The Iseth Reach had already dried, reducing the oasis to deep-well water supply; the battle transformed water scarcity into direct military conflict.
The Pragmatist faction held the oasis briefly, then fragmented under pressure from Charter Wars-period armed charter militias.
The Legalist faction withdrew into administrative exile, producing the doctrinal papers that would eventually influence the Five Cities system's water-right frameworks.
The Ritualist faction's proto-Jackal Synod claimed funerary authority superseded water-right authority and withdrew to the outlying pyramid precincts.
The Great Oasis survived the battle as a geographic fact; it did not survive as a governed institution.
The Cistern Ring's two surviving chambers operate under reduced capacity; the two destroyed chambers' functions have not been restored.
The Toll Pavilion's destruction ended the oasis as a viable administrative center; its regulatory functions were eventually distributed among the Five Cities.
The battle is the marker event for the end of oasis-centered governance and the beginning of the Five Cities-centered governance model.

