---
Midgaard's charter framework was partly designed to prevent another Battle of the Dry Basin.
The oasis's governance failure is the canonical negative example in Midgaard's administrative training: competing authority claims without adjudication mechanism produce violence.
Midgaard maintains water-right records derived from the Legalist faction's administrative exile documents — the most complete surviving legal framework from the pre-battle period.
Continuity faction: the Legalists' documents are legitimate charter precedent; Midgaard's derivation from them is valid.
Reckoning faction: the Legalists' documents were produced in exile under duress; their institutional authority is contested.
The Toll Pavilion's destruction ended the oasis as a viable administrative center; Midgaard inherited its regulatory functions without inheriting its institutional continuity.
Midgaard's position: the Battle of the Dry Basin is the event that made Midgaard necessary.

