---
Kiess's founding narrative treats the Battle of the Dry Basin as the canonical case of single-point governance failure.
The High Water Court held all water-right authority; when it fractured, there was no secondary institution to maintain function.
Kiess's multi-institution design was explicitly built to prevent this: if one institution falls, the others continue.
The battle's most significant lesson for Kiess: institutions that control both enforcement authority and legal determination simultaneously cannot be reformed from within; they can only be replaced from without.
Kiess's three-power charter review requirement is the direct institutional response: no single institution holds authority over both the rule and its enforcement.

